The best approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's a battle-tested library that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface.

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigManager(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var manager = new ConfigManager(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", manager.Load("/data/config.json"));

manager.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

Assert.True(manager.DirectoryExists("/data"));
Assert.False(manager.DirectoryExists("/nope"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?** `System.IO.Abstractions` covers the full `System.IO` API, so you won't need to keep extending your interface every time you use a new method. `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem out of the box — no mocking framework needed.

Once the package is in place, use constructor injection to replace every direct `File.*` / `Directory.*` call with `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*`.
